ublic servants – manipulated what drivers and passengers could and should view from the road. When it came to roads and highways, planners and builders had two concerns: grading or paving a way through “the wilderness” and opening pathways to new parks and historic sites. They understood that the development of a modern road network would lead to new ways of perceiving BC and its environment. Although cars and roads promised freedom, they offered drivers a curated view of the landscape that shaped the province’s image in the eyes of residents and visitors alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAutomobile travelzBritish ColumbiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aAutomobileszBritish ColumbiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aLandscapeszBritish ColumbiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aRoadszBritish ColumbiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aTransportationzBritish ColumbiaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311141793640uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483420940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774834209423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774834209/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-141793-6  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles